Yes, you can modify the code to generate a random grid of numbers instead of letters. Here's the modified code:
#include 
#include 
#include 
using namespace std;
int main() {
 int grid[4][3];
 bool usedNumbers[10] = {false}; // array to keep track of used numbers
 int numberIndex;
 int number;
 // Seed random number generator
 srand(time(NULL));
 // Fill grid with random numbers
 for (int i = 0; i < 4; i++) {
 for (int j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
 // Generate a random number that hasn't been used yet
 do {
 numberIndex = rand() % 10;
 number = numberIndex;
 } while (usedNumbers[numberIndex]);
 usedNumbers[numberIndex] = true;
 grid[i][j] = number;
 }
 }
 // Print grid
 for (int i = 0; i < 4; i++) {
 for (int j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
 cout << grid[i][j] << " ";
 }
 cout << endl;
 }
 return 0;
}

In this modified code, we use an array called `usedNumbers` to keep track of which numbers have already been used. We initialize this array to `false` for all elements at the beginning of the program. Then, when we generate a random number for a cell, we check if that number has already been used by checking the corresponding element in the `usedNumbers` array. If it has been used, we generate a new random number until we find one that hasn't been used yet. Once we find a new number, we mark it as used in the `usedNumbers` array and assign it to the current cell in the grid.

