ground_truth:
In Scala, you can handle errors when reading from a file using the try-catch-finally construct or by using the Either monad.

Here's an example of using try-catch-finally to read from a file in Scala:
import scala.io.Source
try {
 val source = Source.fromFile("file.txt")
 source.getLines.foreach(println)
} catch {
 case e: Exception => println(e.getMessage)
} finally {
 source.close()
}

The above code attempts to read the contents of the file "file.txt". If an exception is thrown during the operation, the catch block will handle the error and print an error message to the console. The finally block is used to ensure that the source is closed regardless of whether or not an exception was thrown.

Here's an example of using the Either monad to read from a file in Scala:
import scala.io.Source
def readFile(filename: String): Either[String, List[String]] = {
 try {
 val source = Source.fromFile(filename)
 val lines = source.getLines.toList
 Right(lines)
 } catch {
 case e: Exception => Left(e.getMessage)
 }
}
val result = readFile("file.txt")
result match {
 case Right(lines) => lines.foreach(println)
 case Left(errorMessage) => println(errorMessage)
}

The above code defines a method called readFile that returns an Either object containing either an error message or a list of lines from the file. If an exception is thrown during the operation, the Left constructor is used to return the error message. Otherwise, the Right constructor is used to return the list of lines. The result is pattern matched to determine whether the operation was successful, and the lines are printed to the console if so.

